						<tr>
							<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I realize I'm only level 33 which means a lot of higher level scouts will instantly discount what I say, but the fact is, I know the EQ universe pretty well.  I played a bard in EQ1 for over 4 years, killed most of the Norrath gods during my tenure there, and led raids in a POP-capable small guild.  So I think I have a good conceptual grasp of how classes work together and how they add value in this game.
<br />

<br />
That said, I'm uncomfortable with what I see ahead for my character.  Understand that right now, I enjoy this game quite a bit.  In groups, I make a very significant contribution and I'm capable of soloing mobs two or three levels above me with minimal difficulty.  But sometimes when you hear complaints, you write it off as malcontents sounding off or whiners unhappy with their situation.  Other times, as has usually been the case on this message board, the concerns come backed with facts and numbers.  What Sonsi has been saying about dirges in EQ2 is very similiar, in fact, to what Thott used to write about bards in the first couple of years of EQ1 -- bottom line, what it comes down to is that Sony has never let the power of utility classes scale at the same rate as the specialists.
<br />

<br />
Let me be specific -- the durability of a tank increases far faster per level than ours does.  The damage output of a wizard/warlock increases far faster per level than ours does.  Okay, you point out that that is the primary thing they do - that we shouldn't be as good at those things as they are.  I totally agree.  I should have a lower damage output, for example, than a level 33 warlock.  But at level 50, my damage should be PROPORTIONALLY as inferior to a warlock's as it is now, instead of comparing far worse than it does now.  The things I do to enhance a group now should be proportionally AS SIGNIFICANT at level 50 as they are at level 33.  And it is pretty obvious from the posts of the guys who are already level 50 that it isn't.
<br />

<br />
So I guess what I am saying is that they have some very valid concerns and I share them.
<br />

<br />
However, my conclusions are different because I've always been one of those crazy optimistic "glass-half-full" kinda guys, even when dealing with Sony.  This game is six months old.  That seems like a lot of time, but there are still not that many 40+ dirges in the game and the data that it takes to narrow down and make the adjustments needed are hard to gather in just 6 months live.  The fact is, there will be a lot more live updates before we can close the book on Sony's willingness to make scouts in general and dirges specifically more viable classes, at least in my opinion.  I think the process of adjusting, balancing, and tweaking classes is far from over.  We won't agree with all of the changes.  But I sincerely believe that if we ARE significantly less than effective in the high end-game raids, there will necessarily be changes down the road.
<br />

<br />
In the meantime, I understand the frustrations of those who are there.  That's the price you pay for being one of the first of your class to hit the high end-game.  Not even the best programmers can accurately anticipate the evolution of player tactics and group dynamics in an MMORPG.  Should we expect Sony to have done a better job?  Possibly so.  Are there going to be more changes down the line?  Without question.  Will that make scouts and bards in particular better class choices in the future?  That remains to be seen.  But know this: customer relations people and programmers read class-specific boards.  People like Sonsi, no matter how negative and frustrated they may become, provide essential, valid, and highly needed input for those people.  I WANT devs and CS people to read Sonsi's comments and understand that he is frustrated.  I want them questioning why this is. 
<br />

<br />
It offers hope that when I hit 50 this will be an even better game.<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://www.mausturm.com/EQ2/images/dingsig1.jpg"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
						</tr>
					</table></td>
				</tr>
